docs.abstract: A dispute over legislation to make lynching a federal crime has grown fierce as Congress turns its attention to issues of race and law enforcement amid protests across the country.
docs.snippet: A dispute over legislation to make lynching a federal crime has grown fierce as Congress turns its attention to issues of race and law enforcement amid protests across the country.
docs.lead_paragraph: As Congress prepares to wade into a contentious debate over legislation to address police brutality and systemic racial bias, a long-simmering dispute in the Senate over a far less controversial bill that would for the first time explicitly make lynching a federal crime has burst into public view.

headline.main: Frustration and Fury as Rand Paul Holds Up Anti-Lynching Bill in Senate
headline.print_headline: Frustration and Fury as Paul Holds Up Anti-Lynching Bill in Senate

docs.abstract: Ava DuVernay, Stanley Nelson, Sabaah Folayan and Damon Davis have all made movies that help explain our nation’s current efforts to face hundreds of years of inequity. Here’s what they said.
docs.snippet: Ava DuVernay, Stanley Nelson, Sabaah Folayan and Damon Davis have all made movies that help explain our nation’s current efforts to face hundreds of years of inequity. Here’s what they said.
docs.lead_paragraph: When 17-year-old Darnella Frazier filmed the police killing of George Floyd on her phone in May, her video reignited the Black Lives Matter movement and nationwide protests, even prompting one supporter to name her “the Rosa Parks of her generation.” In addition to setting off policy debates about police reform, the protests have also renewed interest in books, visual art and movies, especially documentaries about race and social justice.

headline.main: We Asked Four Documentarians: How Does Film Shape the Fight for Racial Justice?
headline.print_headline: Filmmakers With a Focus On Justice

docs.lead_paragraph: HOUSTON — George Floyd died at the hands of police officers in Minneapolis. A thousand miles to the south, in the Texas city where he was raised, two rows of police officers saluted as his coffin went past.

docs.lead_paragraph: George Floyd, 46, died after being handcuffed on the street in the custody of the Minneapolis police on Memorial Day. An officer responding to a report that Mr. Floyd had tried to pass a fake $20 bill helped hold him down by lodging a knee on his neck for nearly nine minutes.

headline.main: How Did George Floyd Die? Here’s What We Know

docs.abstract: The systemic racism that goes hand in hand with police brutality in the region is often overlooked.
docs.snippet: The systemic racism that goes hand in hand with police brutality in the region is often overlooked.
docs.lead_paragraph: CAMBRIDGE, Mass. — On May 18, a 14-year-old boy was playing pool with his cousin and other teenagers in a backyard in São Gonçalo, in the metropolitan region of Rio de Janeiro. Police officers, in pursuit of a drug dealer, fired over 70 shots into the home, killing him. He was black. His name was João Pedro Matos Pinto. There have been so many others.

headline.main: Latin America Is Ready for Its Black Lives Matter Reckoning

docs.abstract: France has long sought social justice through a commitment to universal ideals. But a younger generation is demanding recognition of racism — and remedies for it.
docs.snippet: France has long sought social justice through a commitment to universal ideals. But a younger generation is demanding recognition of racism — and remedies for it.
docs.lead_paragraph: BOBIGNY, France — Luc Pechangou had never joined a protest before, not even when his own neighborhood just outside Paris was convulsed with anger over the violent arrest of a young black man from the area in 2017.

headline.main: George Floyd Protests Stir a Difficult Debate on Race in France
headline.print_headline: French Secularism Being Challenged as Just ‘Structural Discrimination’
